{"title_page": "United Arab Emirates Presidential Guard", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Presidential Guard Command\n| native_name = {{lang|ar|\u062d\u0631\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0626\u0627\u0633\u0629}} {{in lang|ar}}\n| image = UAE Presidential Guard.svg\n| caption = \n| start_date = {{start date|2011}}\n| dates = \n| allegiance = \n| country = {{flag|United Arab Emirates}} \n| branch =\n| size = \n| type = [[Special operations]]\n| role = [[Amphibious warfare|Amphibious]] and [[Expeditionary warfare|expeditionary]] warfare\n| colors = &nbsp;[[Beige]] and [[Burgundy (color)|Burgundy]]\n| command_structure = \n| garrison = \n| garrison_label = \n| nickname = \n| patron = \n| motto = ''[[Allah]], [[Watan]], [[President of the UAE|Ra'is]]''\n| equipment = \n| equipment_label = \n| battles = {{collapsible list\n  |titlestyle = background:transparent;text-align:left;font-weight:normal;\n  |title = ''See list''\n|[[War in Afghanistan]]<br />[[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)]]<br />[[International military intervention against ISIL]]<br />[[Sinai Insurgency]]\n}}\n| decorations = \n| battle_honours = \n| commander1 = [[Khalifa bin Zayed]]\n| commander1_label = Commander in Chief\n| commander2 = [[Mohammed bin Zayed]]\n| commander2_label = Deputy Commander in Chief\n| commander3 = [[Mike Hindmarsh]]\n| commander3_label = Unit commander\n| identification_symbol = \n| identification_symbol_label = \n}}\n\n[[File:The UAE contingent passes through the Rajpath, on the occasion of the 68th Republic Day Parade 2017, in New Delhi on January 26, 2017.jpg|thumb|The Presidential Guard contingent (last three rows) marching on the [[Rajpath]] during the [[Delhi Republic Day parade]] in 2017.]]\n\nThe '''UAE Presidential Guard (UAE-PG)''' ({{lang-ar|\u062d\u0631\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0626\u0627\u0633\u0629 \u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u062d\u062f\u0629}}) is an elite [[military]] [[special operations]] unit of the [[United Arab Emirates Armed Forces]]. It is a military unit that operates outside the conventional framework of traditional armed forces. It is considered to be a premier fighting unit in the [[Middle East]] and the [[Arab world]].<ref>https://m.jpost.com/Opinion/Behind-the-Lines-Hedging-bets-in-the-gulf-599427/amp</ref> It is also seen as the Emirati version of the [[United States Secret Service]] as its duties include protecting the [[President of the UAE|Ra'is]] albeit they are not limited by that role.<ref>https://www.protenders.com/companies/presidential-guard-command</ref> The [[United States Marine Corps]] officially designates the UAE-PG as its Marine counterpart.\n\n==History==\nUAE-PG was formed in 2011 as a merger of the Amiri Guard, the Special Operations Command, and the Marine Battalion from the [[UAE Navy]].<ref>http://www.uaeafghanistan.ae/en/the-presidential-guard.php</ref>\n\nMultiple foreign officers, including Major General [[Mike Hindmarsh]] from the [[Australian Army]] have served and/or are serving in the guard.<ref>https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2016-02-08/yemen-civil-war-questions-role-australian-soldier-mike-hindmarsh/7141638?pfmredir=sm</ref> In the case of Hindmarsh, he serves as the guard's commander.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-12-14/australian-army-veterans-advising-foreign-army-accused-war-crime/10611142</ref> In October 2011, [[United States State Department]] approved of training support being provided by the [[United States Marine Corps]] for the guard under the Marine Corps Training Mission UAE (MCTM-UAE).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marines.mil/News/Messages/Messages-Display/Article/895109/personnel-sourcing-guidance-in-support-of-marine-corps-training-mission-united/  |work= MARADMIN 620/12, PERSONNEL SOURCING GUIDANCE IN SUPPORT OF MARINE CORPS TRAINING MISSION - UNITED ARAB EMIRATES (MCTM- UAE) |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> At around the same time, the USMC officially designated the UAE-PG as its [[Marines|Marine]] counterpart. \n\nIn January 2017, a 149-member contingent from the Presidential Guard, as well as 35-member band, marched in the presence of Sultan [[Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan]] and President [[Pranab Mukherjee]] on the [[Rajpath]] during the [[Delhi Republic Day parade]] of 2017.<ref>https://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=157687</ref><ref>https://m.khaleejtimes.com/uae-india-ties/uae-military-takes-part-in-republic-day-parade</ref><ref>http://www.alkhaleej.ae/mob/detailed/f53c9315-c755-48f7-a351-9dc93baa2e5a/7ef32bd6-9be5-4f85-ab19-7690aa6ee537</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the UAE-PG has inaugurated the opening of Martyr's Park, dedicated to UAE-PG personnel who were killed in the line of duty.<ref>https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/uae-standing-with-saudi-arabia-in-one-trench-mohamed-bin-zayed-1.1567657361155</ref>\n\n==Deployments==\n\n===Afghanistan===\n{{main article|War in Afghanistan}}\n\nThe UAE-PG participated in the War in Afghanistan in support to the coalition efforts against the [[Taliban]]. Their role has mostly been active in the delivery of [[humanitarian aid]] as well as supporting the development of basic community infrastructure in [[Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uaeafghanistan.ae/en/the-UAE-policy-on-Afghanistan.php|title=THE UAE'S POLICY IN AFGHANISTAN|publisher=uaeafghanistan.ae|access-date=4 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2015 Yemeni Civil War===\n{{main article|Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)}}\n\nThe Presidential Guard has played a role in the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]] in the support of the government of President [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi]].<ref>https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/revealed-mercenaries-commanding-uae-forces-yemen</ref> There are allegations that the UAE-PG has participated in war crimes in the Yemeni Civil War.<Ref>https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/defence/australian-mercenaries-referred-to-icc/news-story/860f915298f7c97a5fcecc4a78f08250</ref>\n\n==Organization==\nThe UAE PG has the UAE Special Operations Command under its control.<ref name=\"GS\">https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/gulf/uae-pg.htm</ref>\n\n===Headquarters===\nThe guard headquarters is located in [[Abu Dhabi]], the capital of the United Arab Emirates. The building consists of a basement, a ground floor and three upper levels. It has a length of about 31,000 square meters.<ref>https://www.rwa.com/rwa/project-detail.php?ids=1035</ref>\n\n===Training===\nTraining of UAE-PG personnel is provided under the USMC's UAE Marine Corps Training Mission - United Arab Emirates (UAE MCTM - UAE) unit.<ref name=\"GS\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Republican Guard (Syria)]]\n*[[Republican Guard (Algeria)]]\n*[[Republican Guard (Egypt)]]\n*[[Republican Guard (Lebanon)]]\n\n==Sources==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Guards of honour]]\n[[Category:Military of the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2011]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Presidential Guard Command\n| native_name = {{lang|ar|\u062d\u0631\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0626\u0627\u0633\u0629}} {{in lang|ar}}\n| image = UAE Presidential Guard.svg\n| caption = \n| start_date = {{start date|2011}}\n| dates = \n| allegiance = \n| country = {{flag|United Arab Emirates}} \n| branch =\n| size = \n| type = [[Special operations]]\n| role = [[Amphibious warfare|Amphibious]] and [[Expeditionary warfare|expeditionary]] warfare\n| colors = &nbsp;[[Beige]] and [[Burgundy (color)|Burgundy]]\n| command_structure = \n| garrison = \n| garrison_label = \n| nickname = \n| patron = \n| motto = ''[[Allah]], [[Watan]], [[President of the UAE|Ra'is]]''\n| equipment = \n| equipment_label = \n| battles = {{collapsible list\n  |titlestyle = background:transparent;text-align:left;font-weight:normal;\n  |title = ''See list''\n|[[War in Afghanistan]]<br />[[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)]]<br />[[International military intervention against ISIL]]<br />[[Sinai Insurgency]]\n}}\n| decorations = \n| battle_honours = \n| commander1 = [[Khalifa bin Zayed]]\n| commander1_label = Commander in Chief\n| commander2 = [[Mohammed bin Zayed]]\n| commander2_label = Deputy Commander in Chief\n| commander3 = [[Mike Hindmarsh]]\n| commander3_label = Unit commander\n| identification_symbol = \n| identification_symbol_label = \n}}\n\n[[File:The UAE contingent passes through the Rajpath, on the occasion of the 68th Republic Day Parade 2017, in New Delhi on January 26, 2017.jpg|thumb|The Presidential Guard contingent (last three rows) marching on the [[Rajpath]] during the [[Delhi Republic Day parade]] in 2017.]]\n\nThe '''UAE Presidential Guard (UAE-PG)''' ({{lang-ar|\u062d\u0631\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0626\u0627\u0633\u0629 \u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u062d\u062f\u0629}}) is an elite [[military]] [[special operations]] unit of the [[United Arab Emirates Armed Forces]]. It is a military unit that operates outside the conventional framework of traditional armed forces. It is considered to be a premier fighting unit in the [[Middle East]] and the [[Arab world]].<ref>https://m.jpost.com/Opinion/Behind-the-Lines-Hedging-bets-in-the-gulf-599427/amp</ref> It is also seen as the Emirati version of the [[United States Secret Service]] as its duties include protecting the [[President of the UAE|Ra'is]] albeit they are not limited by that role.<ref>https://www.protenders.com/companies/presidential-guard-command</ref> The [[United States Marine Corps]] officially designates the UAE-PG as its Marine counterpart.\n\n==History==\nUAE-PG was formed in 2011 as a merger of the Amiri Guard, the Special Operations Command, and the Marine Battalion from the [[UAE Navy]].<ref>http://www.uaeafghanistan.ae/en/the-presidential-guard.php</ref>\n\nMultiple foreign officers, including Major General [[Mike Hindmarsh]] from the [[Australian Army]] have served and/or are serving in the guard.<ref>https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2016-02-08/yemen-civil-war-questions-role-australian-soldier-mike-hindmarsh/7141638?pfmredir=sm</ref> In the case of Hindmarsh, he serves as the guard's commander.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-12-14/australian-army-veterans-advising-foreign-army-accused-war-crime/10611142</ref> In October 2011, [[United States State Department]] approved of training support being provided by the [[United States Marine Corps]] for the guard under the Marine Corps Training Mission UAE (MCTM-UAE).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marines.mil/News/Messages/Messages-Display/Article/895109/personnel-sourcing-guidance-in-support-of-marine-corps-training-mission-united/\u00a0 |work= MARADMIN 620/12, PERSONNEL SOURCING GUIDANCE IN SUPPORT OF MARINE CORPS TRAINING MISSION - UNITED ARAB EMIRATES (MCTM- UAE) |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> At around the same time, the USMC officially designated the UAE-PG as its [[Marines|Marine]] counterpart. \n\nIn January 2017, a 149-member contingent from the Presidential Guard, as well as 35-member band, marched in the presence of Sultan [[Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan]] and President [[Pranab Mukherjee]] on the [[Rajpath]] during the [[Delhi Republic Day parade]] of 2017.<ref>https://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=157687</ref><ref>https://m.khaleejtimes.com/uae-india-ties/uae-military-takes-part-in-republic-day-parade</ref><ref>http://www.alkhaleej.ae/mob/detailed/f53c9315-c755-48f7-a351-9dc93baa2e5a/7ef32bd6-9be5-4f85-ab19-7690aa6ee537</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the UAE-PG has inaugurated the opening of Martyr's Park, dedicated to UAE-PG personnel who were killed in the line of duty.<ref>https://gulfnews.com/uae/government/uae-standing-with-saudi-arabia-in-one-trench-mohamed-bin-zayed-1.1567657361155</ref>\n\n==Deployments==\n\n===Afghanistan===\n{{main article|War in Afghanistan}}\n\nThe UAE-PG participated in the War in Afghanistan in support to the coalition efforts against the [[Taliban]]. Their role has mostly been active in the delivery of [[humanitarian aid]] as well as supporting the development of basic community infrastructure in [[Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uaeafghanistan.ae/en/the-UAE-policy-on-Afghanistan.php|title=THE UAE'S POLICY IN AFGHANISTAN|publisher=uaeafghanistan.ae|access-date=4 May 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2015 Yemeni Civil War===\n{{main article|Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)}}\n\nThe Presidential Guard has played a role in the [[Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|Yemeni Civil War]] in the support of the government of President [[Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi]].<ref>https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/revealed-mercenaries-commanding-uae-forces-yemen</ref> There are allegations that the UAE-PG has participated in war crimes in the Yemeni Civil War.<Ref>https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/defence/australian-mercenaries-referred-to-icc/news-story/860f915298f7c97a5fcecc4a78f08250</ref>\n\n==Organization==\nThe UAE PG has the UAE Special Operations Command under its control.<ref name=\"GS\">https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/gulf/uae-pg.htm</ref>\n\n===Headquarters===\nThe guard headquarters is located in [[Abu Dhabi]], the capital of the United Arab Emirates. The building consists of a basement, a ground floor and three upper levels. It has a length of about 31,000 square meters.<ref>https://www.rwa.com/rwa/project-detail.php?ids=1035</ref>\n\n===Training===\nTraining of UAE-PG personnel is provided under the USMC's UAE Marine Corps Training Mission - United Arab Emirates (UAE MCTM - UAE) unit.<ref name=\"GS\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Republican Guard (Syria)]]\n*[[Republican Guard (Algeria)]]\n*[[Republican Guard (Egypt)]]\n*[[Republican Guard (Lebanon)]]\n\n==Sources==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Guards of honour]]\n[[Category:Military of the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2011]]\n",